   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_696_1819_04_08_page01.jpg"/>
            <opener>
               <dateline>
                  <name type="place" ref="./Placeography.xml#Frognal-Hampstead_ENK"/>Frognal Hampstead
                        <date when="1819-04-08">April 4, 1819</date></dateline>
               <salute>
                  <persName/>
               </salute>
            </opener>
            <p>Dearest <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF2">Mother</persName>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF3">Fanny</persName> is much better
                    - all fever gone - pulse 96 - pain in
                    the side gone - only sick &amp; weak now.
                    <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HollP1">Dr. Holland</persName> says she will do very well
                    provided we take the greatest care that
                    she shall not be harrassed or over excited.
                    <add>He says there has been a great deal of fever and he had feared inflammation on the chest.</add>
                    - He says that we must not remit our
                    care when we are in spirits on seeing
                    her apparently recovered - til her health
                    is <hi rend="underline">settled</hi> we must never be <del>careless</del>secure
                    <del>If the</del> This he impressed most strongly
                    on my mind. If <add>&amp; whenever</add> the pain in her side
                    recurs he orders the application of 4 or 6
                    leeches - and this shall be done.</p>
            <p>Nothing can equal the attention &amp; care
                    <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HollP1">D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Holland</persName> has shown. With this whole
                    family we have been as much at ease
                    as if we had been at home.
                    <persName ref="./Personography.xml#CarrF1">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. Carr</persName> has
                    made me quite competent to do the same
                    and poor dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BillK1">Kitty</persName> how often we have thought
                    of her and how often I have wished for her
                    long arms and for your dextrous hands when
                    I have been settling <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF3">Fanny</persName> in her bed.
                    <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_696_1819_04_08_page02.jpg"/>
                    Thank God she is now out of it - up &amp; dressed
                    in her lilac tabbinet sitting in <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauH1">Honora's</persName>
                    bedchamber while her own is refreshing
                    - she has not eaten half an ounce these
                    3 days - so much the better - fever is starved
                    out &amp; now I hope she will gain strength
                    gradually. Her uncle <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauF1">Francis</persName> has several
                    times come to see her. I have adhered to
                    the stipulation that <persName ref="./Personography.xml#WilsL2">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> L W</persName> should not
                    come. Till she is quite recovered I will
                    not permit <add>him to have a glimpse of her</add> - see what a dragon of a duenna
                    I am grown. How Fear does give courage -
                    My fear of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF3">Fanny's</persName> health has made me
                    bold as a lioness guarding her cubs.</p>
            <p>Now that she assures me that no
                    love lurks at the heart I require that the
                    next meeting should be the last. She has
                    in fact decided &amp; <add>to</add> what purpose further
                    meetings except to wear her out with pity
                    &amp; to make the final disappointment
                    more painful to him. <hi rend="underline">More</hi>painful
                    as it must be - the more he sees of her
                    delightfully amiable disposition.</p>
            <p> I decide therefore that if her health
                    permit we take our farewell breakfast or
                    luncheon at <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Harley-Street_ENK">Harley Street</placeName> on the 13<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> or
                    15<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>go to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#WhitE1">Lady E W</persName> who desired to see us
                    again when the business should be decided
                    and not till then - stay with her till the
                 <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_696_1819_04_08_page03.jpg"/>   
                    17<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>. &amp; that day go to the Hopes at <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Deep-Dene-Dorking_ENK">Deep Dene</placeName>
                    &amp; stay till the first week in May when
                    Lord Carrington has asked us to <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#High-Wycombe_ENK">High Wycombe</placeName>
                    on our way back to <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Byrkley-Lodge_ENK">Byrkley Lodge</placeName>
            </p>
            <p>I find that there is a possibility of getting
                     by a [<unclear>cross</unclear>road from <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Dorking_ENK">Dorking</placeName> to <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#High-Wycombe_ENK">High Wycombe</placeName>
                    &amp; without returning to Town. Therefore
                    as far as I see at present this is our best
                    plan to <hi rend="underline">cut &amp; run</hi> as soon as possible &amp;
                    get <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF3">Fanny</persName> out of the way of torturing or
                    being tortured. Perhaps I said all this
                    to you before but I cannot in the least
                    recollect what I wrote two days ago &amp; it
                    is better to tire you with repetition or
                    even to bewilder you with <choice>
                  <orig>contradic
                        -tions</orig>
                  <reg>contradictions</reg>
               </choice> than to leave you in ignorance <unclear>or</unclear>
                    in doubt of my intentions <add>at least</add> as fast as I form
                    them -</p>
            <p>All I said in my last about a draft of mine
                    to pay Newingtons bill <unclear>efface</unclear> from your
                    memory - all a mistake. <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauF1">Francis</persName> says he
                    has money on that account and has torn
                    my draft -</p>
            <closer>
               <address>
                  <pb n="4" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_1819_04_08_page04.jpg"/>
                  <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF2">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. Edgeworth</persName>
                  <addrLine/>
                  <addrLine/>
                  <addrLine/>
               </address>
            </closer>
         </div>
